    79	## What the smoke exercises
    80	
    81	- Logs in as the tenant admin with `identity.admin_login()`
    82	- Ensures the `testuser2` smoke identity exists and is usable with `identity.ensure_sdktest_identity()`
    83	- Ensures the reusable sandbox exists with `sandbox.ensure_sandbox()`: shared folder `SDK Test (ephemeral)`, KSM app `SDK Test KSM`, gateway visibility, app binding, and share to `testuser2`
    84	- Pre-cleans the sandbox with `sandbox.teardown_records(..., manager=MANAGER_NAME)` to remove orphaned SDK-managed records from prior runs
    85	- Writes a scenario-specific smoke manifest and an empty destroy manifest
    86	- Runs SDK `validate` against the generated manifest
    87	- Runs SDK `plan` and expects exit `2` because the initial plan should contain creates
    88	- Runs SDK `apply --auto-approve` to create the scenario records
    89	- Discovers live state through `CommanderCliProvider.discover()` and verifies every expected SDK-managed scenario record, including nested `pamUser` records for `pamUserNested`
    90	- Runs SDK `plan` again and expects exit `0` for a clean re-plan
    91	- After destroy apply, sweeps the project Resources and Users shared-folder
    92	  UIDs for any remaining SDK-marked records (handles ``reference_existing``
    93	  ``pam_configuration`` rows that empty-manifest plans do not always delete),
    94	  then re-discovers with an **empty** provider ``manifest_source`` so the
    95	  synthetic reference-configuration live row is not injected into the final
    96	  “no SDK-owned rows” check
    97	- Runs SDK `plan --allow-delete` against the empty manifest and expects exit `2` because deletes should be present
    98	- Runs SDK `apply --allow-delete --auto-approve` against the empty manifest
    99	- Re-discovers live state and verifies no records carrying this SDK ownership marker remain
   100	
   101	## Teardown
   102	
   103	`python3 scripts/smoke/smoke.py --teardown` runs the same auth, identity, sandbox, and pre-clean path, then stops after deleting SDK-managed records in the sandbox shared folder. The delete guard lives in `sandbox.teardown_records()`: it lists records in the target shared folder, reads each record's `keeper_declarative_manager` marker, decodes it, and deletes only records whose decoded payload has `manager == MANAGER_NAME`.
   104	
   105	## Troubleshooting
   106	
   107	| symptom | next action |
   108	|---------|-------------|
   109	| `two_factor_code_invalid` | `identity.py` retries on the next TOTP window, once per window, up to 3 attempts; if it persists, re-run with `--force` to reprovision `testuser2` TOTP state |
   110	| `keeper CLI not found on PATH` | Install `keepercommander` via `pip` so the `keeper` executable is available |
   111	| `Required gateway 'Lab GW Rocky' is not visible` | The admin session cannot see the gateway; ensure the admin `commander-config.json` belongs to a user with access, then re-run |
   112	| `Commander returned non-JSON` from `ls` on an empty folder | Already handled internally in `sandbox._loads_json()`: empty output is treated as `[]` |
   113	| Keeper subprocess commands hang | They should not hang after `--batch-mode` plus `KEEPER_PASSWORD`; if they do, check that the `testuser2` Commander config still has a valid `device_token` and `clone_code` |
   114	| SDK command failure | The post-mortem includes the full SDK command, exit code, stdout tail, and stderr tail so the parent/live runner can see Commander/provider details without rerunning blind |
   115	
   116	## Non-negotiable constraints
   117	
   118	No `keeper_dag` imports are allowed in this workflow, all tenant-side mutations must go through Commander CLI calls, the smoke must stay idempotent across reruns by reusing and pre-cleaning its sandbox, and teardown must never delete records that are not explicitly marked as SDK-managed.
